{
  "Nuclear fusion in stars primarily converts hydrogen into:": "",
  "Carbon": "",
  "Oxygen": "",
  "Helium": "",
  "Iron": "",
  "In main-sequence stars, hydrogen nuclei fuse to form helium, releasing enormous energy (E = mc²). This is the dominant energy source for most of a star's lifetime.": "",
  "Elements heavier than iron are primarily formed by:": "",
  "Supernova explosions and neutron star mergers": "",
  "Chemical reactions on Earth": "",
  "Normal stellar fusion": "",
  "Solar wind": "",
  "Fusion up to iron releases energy, but forming heavier elements requires energy input. The extreme conditions of supernovae and neutron star mergers provide this energy via rapid neutron capture (r-process).": "",
  "Transuranium elements have atomic numbers greater than:": "",
  "92 (uranium)": "",
  "82 (lead)": "",
  "100 (fermium)": "",
  "118 (oganesson)": "",
  "Uranium (Z = 92) is the heaviest naturally occurring element in significant quantities. All elements beyond it (neptunium, plutonium, etc.) are synthetic — created in labs.": "",
  "Synthetic elements are elements that:": "",
  "Are created in laboratories using nuclear reactions": "",
  "Are always stable": "",
  "Occur naturally on Earth": "",
  "Have no protons": "",
  "Synthetic elements are produced by bombarding target nuclei with accelerated particles. They are generally unstable, with short half-lives.": "",
  "What device is used to accelerate particles for creating new elements?": "",
  "Particle accelerator": "",
  "Geiger counter": "",
  "Mass spectrometer": "",
  "Nuclear reactor": "",
  "Particle accelerators use electromagnetic fields to speed up charged particles to near the speed of light, then slam them into target atoms to produce new elements.": "",
  "The heaviest naturally occurring element is:": "",
  "Oganesson (Z = 118)": "",
  "Plutonium (Z = 94)": "",
  "Fermium (Z = 100)": "",
  "Uranium (Z = 92)": "",
  "While trace amounts of Np and Pu exist naturally, uranium is the heaviest element found in significant quantities in nature.": "",
  "Stellar nucleosynthesis is the process of:": "",
  "Splitting atoms on Earth": "",
  "Cooling stars": "",
  "Creating elements inside stars through nuclear fusion": "",
  "Destroying elements in space": "",
  "Stars build heavier elements by fusing lighter ones: H → He → C → O → ... → Fe. Each stage requires higher temperatures and pressures.": "",
  "Iron (Fe) is significant in stellar fusion because:": "",
  "Iron is the lightest element": "",
  "Fusing elements heavier than iron consumes energy rather than releasing it": "",
  "Iron cannot exist in stars": "",
  "Iron fusion produces the most energy": "",
  "Iron-56 has the highest binding energy per nucleon. Fusing elements beyond iron is endothermic (energy-consuming), which is why stars cannot sustain fusion past iron and may collapse into supernovae.": "",
  "Superheavy elements (Z > 103) are characterized by being:": "",
  "Found commonly in nature": "",
  "Very stable and long-lived": "",
  "Extremely unstable with very short half-lives": "",
  "Used widely in industry": "",
  "Superheavy elements exist for fractions of a second to minutes. Their enormous nuclear charge creates extreme instability, and they are detected by their decay products.": "",
  "The Big Bang primarily produced which light elements?": "",
  "Uranium and plutonium": "",
  "Carbon and oxygen": "",
  "Iron and nickel": "",
  "Hydrogen and helium (with traces of lithium)": "",
  "Big Bang nucleosynthesis occurred minutes after the Big Bang, producing ~75% hydrogen, ~25% helium, and trace lithium. All heavier elements were made later in stars.": "",
  "What is the definition of nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The combining of two lighter nuclei to form a heavier nucleus, releasing energy": "",
  "The emission of gamma rays from a nucleus": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy nucleus into lighter fragments": "",
  "The absorption of neutrons by a nucleus": "",
  "Nuclear fusion combines light nuclei (e.g., H + H → He) and releases energy because the product has lower mass per nucleon. This powers all main-sequence stars.": "",
  "What is a particle accelerator?": "",
  "A container for storing nuclear waste": "",
  "A device that slows down radioactive decay": "",
  "An instrument that measures atomic mass": "",
  "A machine that speeds up charged particles using electromagnetic fields for nuclear collisions": "",
  "Particle accelerators (like cyclotrons and linear accelerators) use electric and magnetic fields to accelerate ions to enormous speeds before colliding them with target nuclei.": "",
  "What does 'transuranium' mean?": "",
  "Elements that do not exist": "",
  "Isotopes of uranium only": "",
  "Elements lighter than uranium": "",
  "Beyond uranium — elements with atomic number greater than 92": "",
  "The prefix 'trans-' means 'beyond.' Transuranium elements (Np, Pu, Am, Cm, etc.) all have Z > 92 and are synthetic.": "",
  "What is nucleosynthesis?": "",
  "The synthesis of proteins in cells": "",
  "The chemical combination of elements into compounds": "",
  "The formation of new elements through nuclear reactions in stars or the Big Bang": "",
  "The decay of radioactive isotopes": "",
  "Nucleosynthesis encompasses Big Bang nucleosynthesis (light elements), stellar nucleosynthesis (up to iron), and supernova/merger nucleosynthesis (elements heavier than iron).": "",
  "What is the definition of nuclear fission?": "",
  "Radioactive decay only": "",
  "The combining of light nuclei": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy nucleus into lighter nuclei, releasing energy": "",
  "The emission of beta particles": "",
  "Fission splits heavy nuclei (like U-235) into smaller fragments plus neutrons and energy. It is the process used in nuclear power plants and atomic weapons.": "",
  "What is the s-process in nucleosynthesis?": "",
  "Slow neutron capture in red giant stars, building heavier elements over thousands of years": "",
  "Solar fusion of hydrogen, particularly regarding building when": "",
  "Chemical synthesis of compounds under normal circumstances": "",
  "Rapid proton capture in supernovae as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "The s-process (slow process) occurs in AGB stars. Nuclei slowly capture neutrons one at a time, with time to beta-decay between captures, building elements up to bismuth.": "",
  "What is the r-process in nucleosynthesis?": "",
  "Slow proton addition in red dwarfs": "",
  "Rapid neutron capture during supernovae or neutron star mergers, producing the heaviest elements": "",
  "Chemical reactions in laboratories": "",
  "Regular fusion in main-sequence stars": "",
  "The r-process captures many neutrons in seconds during extreme events, forming highly neutron-rich nuclei that then beta-decay to create stable heavy elements like gold and platinum.": "",
  "The element oganesson (Og, Z = 118) is notable because it:": "",
  "Is the heaviest element currently confirmed on the periodic table": "",
  "Is the most stable synthetic element": "",
  "Was discovered in the 1800s": "",
  "Is found naturally in seawater": "",
  "Oganesson was first synthesized in 2002 and officially named in 2016. Only a few atoms have ever been created; it decays in milliseconds.": "",
  "Why does fusion require extremely high temperatures (millions of degrees)?": "",
  "To remove all electrons first": "",
  "To melt the nuclei into liquid": "",
  "To overcome the electrostatic repulsion between positively charged nuclei": "",
  "To slow the nuclei down enough to combine": "",
  "Nuclei are positively charged and repel each other. Only at extreme temperatures do they move fast enough to overcome this Coulomb barrier and get close enough for the strong nuclear force to bind them.": "",
  "The 'island of stability' refers to:": "",
  "A predicted region of superheavy elements with relatively long half-lives": "",
  "A group of naturally occurring stable elements": "",
  "The noble gases on the periodic table": "",
  "Stable isotopes of iron": "",
  "Theoretical models predict that certain superheavy nuclei with 'magic numbers' of protons and neutrons should be more stable than neighboring elements, forming an 'island' amid a 'sea' of instability.": "",
  "Scientists at a research lab bombard calcium-48 nuclei into californium-249 targets. The new element formed has an atomic number of:": "",
  "Ca has Z = 20, Cf has Z = 98. Combined: 20 + 98 = 118 (oganesson). This is the actual reaction used to first create element 118.": "",
  "Astronomers detect gold in the debris of a neutron star merger. This supports the theory that gold is formed by:": "",
  "The r-process (rapid neutron capture) during extreme astrophysical events": "",
  "Chemical reactions in Earth's core": "",
  "Slow cooling of stars": "",
  "Normal hydrogen fusion in the Sun": "",
  "Gold (Z = 79) is too heavy to form by normal stellar fusion. The 2017 observation of gravitational waves from a neutron star merger (GW170817) confirmed r-process production of heavy elements including gold.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant uses U-235 fission. If the chain reaction produces too many neutrons, what happens?": "",
  "Fusion begins": "",
  "The reaction accelerates uncontrollably (meltdown risk)": "",
  "Nothing — extra neutrons are harmless": "",
  "The reactor shuts down automatically": "",
  "In fission, each U-235 split releases 2-3 neutrons that can trigger more fissions. Without control rods absorbing excess neutrons, the chain reaction grows exponentially.": "",
  "Researchers are trying to achieve fusion on Earth for clean energy. The main challenge is:": "",
  "Fusion produces too much waste": "",
  "Finding enough hydrogen": "",
  "Sustaining the extreme temperatures and pressures needed to confine plasma": "",
  "Fusion reactions are too slow": "",
  "Fusion requires temperatures over 100 million °C to overcome Coulomb repulsion. Containing this plasma with magnetic fields (tokamaks) or lasers (inertial confinement) remains the primary engineering challenge.": "",
  "Technetium (Z = 43) is notable because it is the lightest element with:": "",
